## 10. Legal + Security Documents

**Why:** Fortune 500 legal/procurement requires these before signing any contract.

Create (as pages or downloadable docs on your marketing site):
- Privacy Policy (GDPR-compliant, covers data storage in Neon/US, AI processing)
- Terms of Service
- Data Processing Agreement (DPA) — required for EU customers
- Security Policy (encryption at rest/in transit, access controls, incident response)
- Subprocessors list (Netlify, Neon, Stripe, Google Gemini via Kaixu gateway, SendGrid)
- SLA document (uptime commitment, support response times)

---

## 11. Penetration Test / Security Audit

**Why:** Enterprise procurement will ask "have you had a pentest?" — answer must be yes.

Options (cheapest to most thorough):
- Run OWASP ZAP (free, automated) against your staging URL — generates a report
- Burp Suite Community Edition — manual testing of auth flows
- Pay for a real pentest from a firm (~$3k-15k) for a report you can share with customers
- At minimum: run `npm audit` on all dependencies, fix criticals

---

## 12. Multi-Region / Disaster Recovery

**Why:** Single-region = single point of failure. Enterprise SLAs require < 1hr RTO.

Build:
- Neon: enable read replicas (already available on Neon paid plans)
- Document RTO/RPO targets in your DRP runbook
- Runbook.md: step-by-step what to do if Netlify is down / Neon is down / Stripe is down
- Incident response plan: who gets paged, what's the escalation path

